00:00:22.570 --> 00:00:24.710
So what are the topics for today?

00:00:24.710 --> 00:00:28.929
So we'll talk about contacts, if you couldn't
tell that from the session description.

00:00:28.929 --> 00:00:32.159
So we'll go over contacts, how
we use them, where we use them.

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:37.109
We'll go over where we use them on the
iPhone, what are new features on iPhone 3.0

00:00:37.109 --> 00:00:40.130
and Address Book in Snow Leopard, new features there.

00:00:40.130 --> 00:00:45.120
And final, we'll conclude with the Address
Book Server in Mac OS X Server in Snow Leopard.

00:00:45.119 --> 00:00:49.719
So a little bit of a background for people
who don't know what really contacts are.

00:00:49.719 --> 00:00:51.769
So, personal contacts.

00:00:51.770 --> 00:00:55.890
So this is basically people you interact in day and day out.

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:59.329
So this could this be your family, this could
be your friends, could be your colleagues,

00:00:59.329 --> 00:01:03.070
basically people you interact with regular basis.

00:01:03.070 --> 00:01:08.900
Contacts for these people, you'd keep them on your
phone, on your desktop so they could be on any device.

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:14.320
And if you have multiple devices that
you have your contacts on, you sync them.

00:01:14.319 --> 00:01:18.289
So you have an iPhone, you sync that
with your Mac OS X Address Book.

00:01:18.290 --> 00:01:25.120
On Windows you would have iTunes sync to the Windows Address
Book and you might also use some services on the cloud,

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:31.850
such as MobileMe or Google and Yahoo and
use those to store your contacts centrally.

00:01:31.849 --> 00:01:36.869
And you also have Work Contacts and the
distinction here is that, in your office,

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:38.680
you probably have something like a directory.

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:45.420
So this includes like everybody in your company that you
may interact with at some point, email or chat or call,

00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:47.159
but you don't necessarily have them in your--

00:01:47.159 --> 00:01:52.219
in your Contacts Data Base in your Address
Book or on the Contacts on the iPhone.

00:01:52.219 --> 00:01:56.620
And you-- in the workplace you might also
have some contacts that are private to you.

00:01:56.620 --> 00:02:03.939
So the distinction here is that your private work
contacts may be some things like business partners

00:02:03.939 --> 00:02:12.189
and these aren't your personal contacts, you don't interact
with these kind of contacts in your off-work-hours life.

00:02:12.189 --> 00:02:19.539
But they are people that you work with in your
work environment and might not have available

00:02:19.539 --> 00:02:22.329
in the company directory because they're private to you.

00:02:22.330 --> 00:02:25.700
And in your work environment, your
contacts would be stored on a server.

00:02:25.699 --> 00:02:32.269
So right now, that's most typically Exchange
setup and coming up with Mac OS X Snow Leopard,

00:02:32.270 --> 00:02:36.130
you might also store the contacts on Address Book Server.

00:02:36.129 --> 00:02:39.490
So that's personal and work contacts.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:41.330
So where do you use these contacts?

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:46.870
Well basically it's anywhere, everywhere, so
you search for contacts and you might mail them.

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:47.789
You do chatting.

00:02:47.789 --> 00:02:49.729
You schedule with your contacts.

00:02:49.729 --> 00:02:51.159
You try to find a location.

00:02:51.159 --> 00:02:54.099
You map your contacts if it's a restaurant.

00:02:54.099 --> 00:02:58.639
You call them on your iPhone and you
might share your contacts using vCards.

00:02:58.639 --> 00:03:04.399
So contacts are all around us all the time
and it's kind of, it's like ubiquitous thing

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:08.120
that we don't really pay attention to,
well except when things don't work,

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:11.599
but it's just pervasive in our day-in-day-out lives.

00:03:11.599 --> 00:03:14.000
So we email people, we use contacts.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.240
We chat or call people, we use contacts.

00:03:16.240 --> 00:03:18.800
We find locations, we use contacts.

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:21.219
So that's using contacts.

00:03:21.219 --> 00:03:24.770
