00:13:57.929 --> 00:14:00.409
So about Server Contacts.

00:14:00.409 --> 00:14:03.819
So typically, why would you have a server?

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:11.520
So this is ideal where you have multiple devices
that are using some service like mail or contacts

00:14:11.519 --> 00:14:14.439
and using a server account always remain up to date.

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:21.020
So you could have a single account on a server and
all your data no matter where you access it from,

00:14:21.019 --> 00:14:24.159
from what ever device, it's always current.

00:14:24.159 --> 00:14:32.079
And additionally, you may have some server enabled
features, such as, search, or sharing, or what not,

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:36.280
because it's guaranteed to be available
and it's not just restricted

00:14:36.279 --> 00:14:39.379
to applications that you'd use like mail for messaging.

00:14:39.379 --> 00:14:45.189
You might have things like global address lists on
Exchange that are only provided through a server

00:14:45.190 --> 00:14:49.650
that you wouldn't be able to implement
just using your local context for example.

00:14:49.649 --> 00:14:58.250
So, servers are pretty cool things for
doing more advanced usage of these services.

00:14:58.250 --> 00:15:00.720
So for Mac OS X.

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:03.090
So we have a suite of communication applications.

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:09.550
So we have your mail application, you
have calendaring, chatting, and contacts.

00:15:09.549 --> 00:15:13.949
So for all of these we also have
great servers on Mac OS X Server.

00:15:13.950 --> 00:15:20.460
So we have a mail server that your mail clients
can connect to and retrieve and send mail.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:26.680
We have a calendar server, so you can now
have scheduling in a server environment

00:15:26.679 --> 00:15:30.549
or leverage in a server, we have a chat server.

00:15:30.549 --> 00:15:34.099
And all of these basically implement their typical things.

00:15:34.100 --> 00:15:39.080
But for contacts, we really don't have
anything right now-- for protocols, excuse me.

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:44.889
So for protocols, we have always
followed the standards path.

00:15:44.889 --> 00:15:48.850
So for our messaging protocols,
we're not doing anything proprietary.

00:15:48.850 --> 00:15:57.670
We're using the IETF standards or the RFCs for either
messaging or for calendaring or for instant messaging.

00:15:57.669 --> 00:16:03.279
So everything that we built in to the server
is open standards based, it's extensible.

00:16:03.279 --> 00:16:07.949
So we don't embrace and extinguish, we embrace and extend.

00:16:07.950 --> 00:16:13.590
So you have the freedom of choice and you're
not locked-in into any particular platform.

00:16:13.590 --> 00:16:15.370
So standards are important to us.

00:16:15.370 --> 00:16:19.360
So if you choose OS X server, you're
choosing open standards.

00:16:19.360 --> 00:16:25.779
But for contacts, there really hasn't been
an equivalent of a CalDav or IMAP or SMTP.

00:16:25.779 --> 00:16:33.000
But just in the past couple of years, there has been
development on the IETF work groups to develop a standard

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:37.480
for contacts based on servers and
that standard is called CardDAV.

00:16:37.480 --> 00:16:41.769
And we've build the Mac OS X Address
Book Server on top of CardDAV.

00:16:41.769 --> 00:16:46.809
And that's what we introduced last year,
and that's what we're now had made available

00:16:46.809 --> 00:16:49.679
to you on the DVDs distributed here.

00:16:49.679 --> 00:16:52.479
So let's look back.

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:58.649
So we built the Calendar server in
Mac OS X Server Leopard in 10.5.

00:16:58.649 --> 00:17:01.860
And what is Calendar server really?

00:17:01.860 --> 00:17:08.690
In the essence of it, it's a protocol that allows you
access to web stored resources, and that's WebDAV.

00:17:08.690 --> 00:17:12.870
And the data format is pretty much calendar events.

00:17:12.869 --> 00:17:18.349
So iCalendar files that are reachable by
the clients over the network using WebDAV.

00:17:18.349 --> 00:17:19.359
So that gives us CalDAV.

00:17:19.359 --> 00:17:22.409
There are other pieces to CalDAV
for, like discovering free visit

00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:23.380
[ phonetic] and whatnot.

00:17:23.380 --> 00:17:29.160
But in the essence of it, it's dealing
with iCalendar files over the network.

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:31.370
So that's what's left.

00:17:31.369 --> 00:17:34.559
And that's a standard that's been out there for a while.

00:17:34.559 --> 00:17:41.730
And for contacts, we already have a standard
for contact Exchange, so that's vCard.

00:17:41.730 --> 00:17:46.690
So vCard was developed years and years ago
by a consortium, Apple is a part of that.

00:17:46.690 --> 00:17:52.759
And if we look at Exchanging vCards over the network, we
could utilize exactly the same infrastructure that we have

00:17:52.759 --> 00:17:59.480
for CalDAV that is using WebDAV as
the network transport mechanism.

00:17:59.480 --> 00:18:04.549
And instead of moving iCal files
around and doing scheduling,

00:18:04.549 --> 00:18:08.829
we can move vCards around and do contact discovery.

00:18:08.829 --> 00:18:11.929
So that gives us CardDAV.

00:18:11.930 --> 00:18:18.320
So vCard's really a ubiquitous standard for
changing or exchanging contact information.

00:18:18.319 --> 00:18:24.809
So this is something that pretty much
every device known to man understands

00:18:24.809 --> 00:18:27.289
and writes if they have anything to with contacts.

00:18:27.289 --> 00:18:29.420
Your phone will understand vCards.

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:35.960
Your laptop, be it Windows or was it running
Windows or Mac OS X will understand vCards.

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:41.360
So vCards, you can pass them around and expect
that the information will be transferred

00:18:41.359 --> 00:18:45.529
from application to application without any issues.

00:18:45.529 --> 00:18:50.720
There's one unique thing in vCards in
the CardDAV server in the CardDAV space.

00:18:50.720 --> 00:18:55.950
So in CardDAV, we need to be able
to uniquely identify vCards.

00:18:55.950 --> 00:18:59.440
So there's a requirement for any
vCard that's stored on the server.

00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:02.450
So it has a unique ID attached to that.

00:19:02.450 --> 00:19:07.740
Most of the clients will take care of that
when they store the contacts on the server.

00:19:07.740 --> 00:19:09.620
So, a little bit more about the CardDAV.

00:19:09.619 --> 00:19:13.699
So CardDAV again, is based on existing standards.

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:19.200
We use XML, we use HTTP, we use
WebDAV, and ACLs on top of that.

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:22.080
And as the payload, we have vCard.

00:19:22.079 --> 00:19:28.669
So it tells you how to use Address
Book collections over the network.

00:19:28.670 --> 00:19:32.960
So it also defines where these resources are stored.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:40.900
So it tells the client where their Address Book
collections are and defines a hierarchy of objects.

00:19:40.900 --> 00:19:45.810
So in the end there will be vCards in some path on a server.

00:19:45.809 --> 00:19:50.539
So CardDAV defines that nomenclature as well.

00:19:50.539 --> 00:19:56.940
And finally, CardDAV has extensions,
just like CalDAV has extensions

00:19:56.940 --> 00:20:00.190
for calendaring, for freebies [phonetic], and whatnot.

00:20:00.190 --> 00:20:04.970
CardDAV has extensions for contact-specific domain.

00:20:04.970 --> 00:20:12.660
So for example, if you want to do a search, there's
a CardDAV feature for doing search against contacts.

00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:14.610
And these are called "reports.

00:20:14.609 --> 00:20:19.909
>> So we use reports to discover your
Address Book collection for example.

00:20:19.910 --> 00:20:22.850
We use reports to do searches against the server.

00:20:22.849 --> 00:20:30.359
So these are extensions on top of the DAV
protocol and that are unique to CardDAV.

00:20:30.359 --> 00:20:37.349
So, here are all the nomenclatures
about vCard, WebDAV, and CardDAV.

00:20:37.349 --> 00:20:46.619
So all the good RFCs are there, SSL, there's DAV,
there's HTTP, and extensions that we use in CardDAV.

00:20:46.619 --> 00:20:52.029
So the server implements a method for
creating new Address Book collections.

00:20:52.029 --> 00:21:01.309
So creating an Address Book on the server and that is
using the-- make a collection extension to DAV protocol.

00:21:01.309 --> 00:21:08.279
And all of these are still-- the vCard protocol
itself, excuse me, CardDAV specification is still

00:21:08.279 --> 00:21:15.139
in ratification going through final runs of comments
and should be standardized as an RFC momentarily

00:21:15.140 --> 00:21:19.970
in the next weeks or months, but soon, we hope.

